## What

When a fn is *never* used as a continuation anywhere in the module (e.g. `main`), its `emit_return` always sees `cont_ptr == null` at runtime — the trampoline entry sets it to null and nothing else writes to its frame's slot 0. The current `emit_return` (src/ir_codegen.rs:3122) handles both cases (null = halt, non-null = write-and-return-cont-frame), so it emits a `load v0+16; iconst 0; icmp eq; brif` dispatch on every Return — for `main` this is unreachable plumbing.

For fixtures/add1.fz's `main`, the dump shows:

```
v5 = load.i64 notrap aligned v0+16    ; cont_ptr (statically null)
v6 = iconst.i64 0
v7 = icmp eq v5, v6                   ; always true
brif v7, block1, block2

block1: call fz_halt; return null      ; always taken
block2: store result; return cont      ; dead code
```

When this spec's FnId is never the cont of any `Term::Call` / `Term::CallClosure` / `Term::Receive` in the module, emit a halt-only path: `call fz_halt(host_ctx, val); return null`. The whole load/icmp/brif/two-block structure goes away.

## Analysis

Re-introduce a per-FnId set `cont_target_fns: HashSet<FnId>` computed at the top of `compile_with_backend`:

```rust
let mut cont_target_fns = HashSet::new();
for f in &module.fns {
    for blk in &f.blocks {
        match &blk.terminator {
            Term::Call { continuation, .. }
            | Term::CallClosure { continuation, .. }
            | Term::Receive { continuation } => {
                cont_target_fns.insert(continuation.fn_id);
            }
            _ => {}
        }
    }
}
```

(This is the same shape as the pre-.27.14.1 `cont_target_fns`, restored for a different consumer. The two analyses now coexist: per-spec `uniform_cont_reachable` for the slot-0 force-Tagged decision; per-FnId `cont_target_fns` for the entry-fn emit_return specialization.)

## Codegen change

Pass `cont_target_fns` into `compile_fn` and use it to gate emit_return calls. At each `emit_return(... frame_ptr, host_ctx, val)` call site, if `!cont_target_fns.contains(&this_fn_id)`, call a new `emit_halt_and_return_null(b, jmod, runtime, host_ctx, val)` helper instead. The helper emits just:

```rust
let halt_fref = jmod.declare_func_in_func(runtime.halt_id, b.func);
b.ins().call(halt_fref, &[host_ctx, val]);
let null = b.ins().iconst(types::I64, 0);
b.ins().return_(&[null]);
```

No frame_ptr read; no dispatch.

## Tests (TDD)

1. CLIF assertion on fixtures/add1.fz: `main` body has **no** `load.i64 notrap aligned v0+16` (the cont_ptr load), no `icmp eq` over a freshly-materialized zero, no `brif`. Just `iconst 41; call fn0; call fn1; call fz_halt; return null`.
2. Behavioural: add1.fz prints 42.
3. Regression: a fixture where the same fn is BOTH the entry AND a cont (if any exist) — verify it still emits the dispatch. If no such fixture exists, leave a note in the ticket comment.
4. Spec-parity + fixture matrix all green.

## Acceptance

- `cargo test` green, no warnings.
- `main` for add1.fz: no `load`, no `icmp`, no `brif`, no `block1`/`block2` split. Linear body.
- No regression in any fn that IS a cont target.

## Risks / verification done

- `main` by construction isn't a cont target in any lowered program (typer never lowers it as a cont).
- For tests that run `compile().run(some_other_fn)`: if `some_other_fn` is never used as a cont in the module's IR, this specialization applies and is safe (it IS the entry; cont_ptr IS null). If it IS used as a cont elsewhere, the specialization doesn't apply (FnId is in `cont_target_fns`), and behavior is unchanged.
- The `frame_ptr: Option<ir::Value>` plumbing from .27.16 stays; the new `emit_halt_and_return_null` helper doesn't take `frame_ptr` at all (cleaner).

## Blocks

Blocked by .27.17 (the dedup) only loosely — they touch the same helper. Best landed in order so .17.2's "no load/icmp/brif" assertion doesn't conflict with .17.1's "one iconst.i64 0" assertion (the .17.2 case has zero, the .17.1 case has one).
